Sample Project

Michael T. Gastner

Relationship between Female Participation in Education and in Politics

Purpose of This Presentation

As highlighted by Goetz (2003), qualitative evidence from developing countries indicates that education plays a crucial role in supporting women’s engagement in informal political activities.1

This presentation aims to explore the relationship between female education and women’s representation in politics, offering insights into the significance of education and potential avenues for enhancing female participation.

  1. Goetz, Anne Marie (2003). UNESCO 2004/ED/EFA/MRT/PI/23, p. 16. URL: https://unesdoc.unesco.org/ark:/48223/pf0000146770. Accessed on 09 July 2023.

Research Questions

To what extent does female participation in education, spanning from early childhood to adulthood, influence the representation of women in politics?

Specifically, what is the relationship between the level of female education and the proportion of seats held by women in local and national political institutions?

Can population, income group and region serve as predictors of female participation in education and politics?

Importance of This Research

  • Empowerment:
    Explores education’s role in empowering women politically.
  • Gender Equality:
    Examines the interplay between women’s educational opportunities and their representation in politics.
  • Policy Implications:
    Informs gender parity policies through targeted strategies tailored to a country’s socio-economic context.
  • Social Progress:
    Reflects inclusivity and contributes to societal advancement.

UN Sustainable Development Goals

Female participation in education and politics are related to Goals 4 and 5.

UN Targets Addressed

  • Quality Education:
    • Target 4.2: Equal access to quality pre-primary education
    • Target 4.3: Equal access to affordable technical, vocational, and higher education
  • Gender Equality:
    • Target 5.5: Ensure full participation in leadership and decision-making

Selected Indicators

  • 4.2.2: Participation rate in organized learning (one year before the official primary entry age), by sex
  • 4.3.1: Participation rate of youth and adults in formal and non-formal education and training in the previous 12 months, by sex
  • 5.5.1(a): Proportion of seats held by women in national parliaments
  • 5.5.1(b): Proportion of elected seats held by women in deliberative bodies of local government

\(k\)-Means Clustering

Considering the four selected Sustainable Development Goals, what is an appropriate number, \(k\), of clusters for countries?

The ‘elbow criterion’ suggests \(k=3\) or \(k=4\).

We choose \(k=3\), but this decision is admittedly subjective.

Pairs Plot Highlighting Clusters

1. High education and high political representation.

2. Low education and high political representation.

3. Low political representation.

Decision Tree

Can the cluster assignment be predicted based on the country’s income group, population size and region according to the 7-class World Bank categorisation?

Evaluation of Decision Tree

The decision tree does not assign any country to cluster 2 (low education and high political representation).

Ten-fold cross validation indicates that the decision tree has a low accuracy of 0.65.

The relative importance of the predictors for classification are as follows:

  • Income group: 100
  • Region: 60.55
  • Population size: 9.07

Summary of Quantitative Results

  • Strong positive correlations exist between indicators for the same goal.
  • Moderate but statistically significant correlations are observed between indicators for different goals.
  • The country’s income group and region may moderately influence female participation in education and politics.
  • Population size does not have a significant impact.
  • Many missing. Only 72 countries have data for all four indicators.

Policy Implications

  • Education and gender equality indicators are interconnected.
  • Promote gender equality in both national and local political institutions because both levels are strongly correlated.
  • Tailor interventions to address specific challenges in different income groups and regions.
  • Support countries in improving data collection for evidence-based policymaking.
